0fcsseldorf.jpg\n| caption =\n| manufacturer = [[Daimler AG]]\n| production = 2010\u20132018\n| assembly = Germany: [[Sindelfingen]]\n| designer = [[Gorden Wagner]]\n| class = [[Mid-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[E-segment|E]])\n| body_style = {{ubl\n  |4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]\n  |5-door [[shooting brake]]\n  }}\n| layout = {{ubl\n  |[[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n  |[[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, all-wheel-drive]] ([[4matic]])\n  }}\n| platform = \n| related = [[Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W212)]]\n| engine = {{ubl\n  |2.1 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM651 engine|''OM651'']] [[inline-four engine|I4]] [[turbocharger|turbo]] / [[twin-turbo]] (diesel)\n  |3.0 L [[Mercedes-Benz OM642|''OM642'']] [[V6 engine|V6]] [[turbocharger|turbo]] (diesel)\n  |3.0 \u2013 3.5 L [[Mercedes-Benz M276 engine|''M276'']] [[V6 engine|V6]] (petrol)\n  |4.7 L [[Mercedes-Benz M278 engine#M278 (base)|''M278'']] [[V8 engine|V8]] [[twin-turbo]] (petrol)\n  |5.5 L [[Mercedes-Benz M278 engine#M157|''M157'']] [[V8 engine|V8]] [[twin-turbo]] (petrol)\n  }}\n| transmission = {{ubl\n  |7-speed [[7G-Tronic]] [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n  |9-speed [[9G-Tronic]] [[automatic transmission|automatic]]\n  }}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2874|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{ubl\n  |{{convert|4937|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (C218)\n  |{{convert|4953|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (X218)\n  }}\n| width = {{convert|1881|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{ubl\n  |{{convert|1418|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (C218)\n  |{{convert|1419|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (X218)\n  }}\n| weight = {{convert|1660|-|1950|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class (W219)]]\n| successor = [[Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class (C257)]]\n| sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''W218 Mercedes-Benz CLS''' is the second generation of the [[Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class|Mercedes CLS-Class]] range of four-door ([[fastback]] styled) [[sedan (car)|sedans]]. The model shares the chassi and most of the technique with the W212 Mercedes E-class and was produced from 2010 to 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autotrader.ca/newsfeatures/20170810/depreciation-appreciation-2011-2017-mercedes-benz-cls-63-amg-w218/|title=Depreciation Appreciation: 2011-2017 Mercedes-Benz CLS 63 AMG (W218)|work=autoTRADER.ca|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> The body styles of the range are:\n\n* 4-door [[sedan (automobile)|sedan/saloon]] (C218)\n* 5-door [[station wagon|estate/wagon]] (X218, marketed as the CLS Shooting Brake)\n\nUnlike its predecessor, the C218/ X218 CLS can be optioned with [[all-wheel drive]] 4MATIC on all models including CLS63 AMG variants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.topspeed.com/cars/mercedes/2015-mercedes-cls63-amg-ar164010.html|title=2015 Mercedes CLS63 AMG Review @ Top Speed|work=Top Speed|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Mercedes also introduced a new five-door estate version to the CLS lineup, called the CLS Shooting Brake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-review/mercedes-benz/cls-shooting-brake|title=Mercedes-Benz CLS Shooting Brake Review (2018) {{!}} Autocar|website=www.autocar.co.uk|language=en|access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe W218 CLS-Class was succeeded by the [[Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class (C257)|Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class (C257)]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motor-shows-la-motor-show/2018-mercedes-benz-cls-starts-%C2%A357510|title=2018 Mercedes-Benz CLS starts from \u00a357,510 {{!}} Autocar|website=www.autocar.co.uk|language=en|access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Development and launch ==\nThe design of the W218 CLS is based on the [[Mercedes-Benz F800|F800 Style concept car]] unveiled by Mercedes-Benz at the [[Geneva Motor Show#2009|2009 Geneva Motor Show]].<ref>[http://www.autoblog.com/2010/02/20/geneva-preview-mercedes-benz-f800-style-previews-next-cls-class/ Geneva Preview: Mercedes-Benz F 800 Style a sneak peek at next CLS-Class]</ref> It is a four-door coup\u00e9 featuring a new [[Comand APS|COMAND]] interface utilizing a touchpad, design cues inspired by the [[Mercedes-Benz SLS AMG|Mercedes SLS AMG]], and sliding rear doors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/geneva-motor-show/mercedes-f800-news-f800-merc%E2%80%99s-future-style-2010|title=Mercedes F800 news - F800: Merc\u2019s future style - 2010|website=www.topgear.com|language=en|access-date=29 May 2018}}</ref> The production version W218 CLS was publicly unveiled at the [[2010 Paris Motor Show]] and as with the previous generation,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-shows/paris-auto-show/news/a16371/2012-mercedes-benz-cls/|title=2012 Mercedes-Benz CLS|date=28 September 2010|work=Road & Track|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> is based on the [[Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W212)|E-Class]] platform, utilising the same rear [[multi-link suspension]] setup.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.carmagazine.co.uk/car-reviews/long-term-tests/mercedes-benz/mercedes-cls-shooting-brake-2015-long-term-test-review/|title=Mercedes CLS Shooting Brake (2015) long-term test review|work=CAR Magazine|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Body styles ==\n<gallery mode=\"nolines\" widths=\"250\" perrow=\"3\">\nFile:Mercedes-Benz CLS 250 in Pattaya.JPG|C218 sedan\nFile:2013 Mercedes-Benz CLS 250 CDI (X 218) BlueEFFICIENCY station wagon (2015-07-24) 02.jpg|X218 Shooting Brake\n</gallery>\n\n=== Sedan (C218) ===\nProduction started on January 2011, with 4MATIC model sales starting later in September.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.topspeed.com/cars/mercedes/2012-2014-mercedes-benz-cls-ar95368.html|title=2012 - 2014 Mercedes-Benz CLS Review @ Top Speed|work=Top Speed|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Shooting Brake (X218) ===\nThe CLS Shooting Brake was announced on June 2012, and is an estate version of the CLS sedan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carmagazine.co.uk/News/Search-Results/First-Official-Pictures/Mercedes-CLS-Shooting-Brake-2012-first-official-pictures/|title=Mercedes CLS Shooting Brake (2012) first pictures|last=Kew|first=Ollie|date=29 June 2012|work=Car Magazine|accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> It is based on the Concept Shooting Brake unveiled at [[Auto China]] 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://autoweek.com/article/china-auto-show/china-auto-show-mercedes-benz-shooting-break-concept-previews-new-cls-0|title=China auto show: Mercedes-Benz Shooting Break concept previews new CLS|work=Autoweek|access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref> Shooting Brake models went on sale from October 2012, and are available alongside sedan models in all-wheel drive and AMG variants.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.topspeed.com/cars/mercedes/2013-mercedes-cls-63-amg-shooting-brake-ar118307.html|title=2013 Mercedes CLS 63 AMG Shooting Brake Review @ Top Speed|work=Top Speed|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> It is currently not sold in the United States.<ref>[http://www.autoblog.com/2012/09/28/2013-mercedes-benz-cls-shooting-brake-paris-2012/ 2013 Mercedes-Benz CLS Shooting Brake is bringing sexy-functional back]</ref> It is the most expensive serial production station wagon in the world since year 1992.\n\n== Equipment ==\nStandard equipment includes [[headlamp|bi-xenon headlights]], 18-inch alloy wheels, dual zone automatic [[HVAC|climate control]], power sunroof, and satellite navigation with a 10TB hard-drive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parkers.co.uk/mercedes-benz/cls/shooting-brake/review/features-safety-and-equipment/|title=Mercedes-Benz CLS Shooting Brake (2012 - 2018) Features, Equipment and Accessories {{!}} Parkers|website=www.parkers.co.uk|language=en|access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref> Standard safety equipment consists of [[anti-lock braking system|anti-lock brakes]], [[electronic stability control]], [[head restraint#Whiplash protection|active head restraints]], and 10 total front, side, and knee airbags.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autoblog.com/buy/2016-Mercedes_Benz-CLS_Class/safety-features/|title=2016 Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class Safety Features|website=Autoblog|language=en|access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref> CLS models also come with [[driver drowsiness detection#Systems|driver fatigue detection]] and [[lane departure warning system]] functions as standard.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2011/10/04/mercedes-benz-driving-drowsy/|title=Why Is My Car Telling Me To Get Coffee?|work=Autoblog|access-date=31 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> Available options include Mercedes' AirMATIC [[air suspension]], [[traffic-sign recognition|traffic sign recognition]], and a reversing camera in conjunction with the COMAND APS system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rac.co.uk/drive/car-reviews/mercedes-benz/cls-class/10629/|title=Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class 350 BlueTEC review {{!}} Car review {{!}} RAC Drive|website=www.rac.co.uk|language=en|access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parkers.co.uk/mercedes-benz/cls/features-safety-and-equipment/|title=Mercedes CLS review: features, gadgets and practicality  {{!}} Parkers|website=www.parkers.co.uk|language=en|access-date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Models ==\n=== Petrol engines ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Model\n!Years\n!Engine\n!Power\n!Torque\n!0-100 km/h (0-62 mph)\n|-\n|CLS350 <br> BlueEFFICIENCY\n|2011\u20132014\n|[[Mercedes-Benz M272 engine#E35|M276 DE35]] <br> 3.5&nbsp;L [[V6 engine|V6]]\n|{{convert|225|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> @ 6,500 rpm\n|{{convert|370|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> @ 3,500\u20135,250 rpm\n|6.1 s\n|-\n|CLS400\n|2014\u20132017\n|[[Mercedes-Benz M276 engine|M276 E30]] <br> 3.0&nbsp;L [[V6 engine|V6]]\n|{{convert|245|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> @ 5,250\u20136,000 rpm\n|{{convert|480|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} <br> @ 1,200\u20134,000 rpm\n|5.3 s\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |CLS500 <br> BlueEFFICIENCY\n|2011\u20132014\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Mercedes-Benz M278 engine#M278 (base)|M278 DE46]] <br> 4.7&nbsp;L [[V8 engine|V8]] [[twin-turbo]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |{{convert|300|kW|hp|0|abbr=on}} <br> @ 5,000\u20135,75